  "notes": "Central Standard Swedish. COMPLEMENTARY QUANTITY: in a stressed syllable a long vowel is followed by a short consonant and a short vowel by a long consonant or a cluster (Riad 2014; Wikipedia: 'a phonologically short consonant follows a long vowel and a long consonant follows a short vowel'). Encoded with data only: doubled consonant letters are grapheme keys mapping to /Cː/ (⟨ck⟩→/kː/), consonant clusters are grapheme keys mapping to the concatenated phonemes, the stressed nucleus takes the long vowel via `positional_graphemes.nucleus_stressed`, and allophone rules shorten it again when the next phoneme is one of those long/cluster phonemes. SOFTENING: ⟨k g sk⟩ → [ɕ j ɧ] before a front vowel (e i y ä ö) — expressed with the BEFORE_FRONT_VOWEL class, so ⟨å⟩ (axis-ambiguous) correctly keeps the hard reading. RETROFLEXION: /r/+coronal → [ʈ ɖ ɳ ɭ ʂ]. PRE-R LOWERING: ⟨ä⟩/⟨ö⟩ lower to [æ(ː)]/[œ(ː)] before /r/ and the retroflexes. NO FINAL DEVOICING: Swedish keeps final /b d ɡ/ (the previous spec devoiced them — that was wrong). TONE: accent 1/2 is lexical and is not encoded; the gold marks it (¹/²), which is a convention difference.",
  "quality": "research",
